	(254,1,'2015-03-18 19:54:33','2015-03-18 19:54:33','Every year, the Interactive part of the festival grows bigger, and this year was no exception. If you\'ve never been, know this: it’s not a place for the faint of heart. This is a day-to-night affair, non-stop, for four days. It\'s panels, parties and pop-ups throughout the city, and it’s a great way to meet and connect with people you would never have met otherwise.\r\n<!--more-->\r\nBy request, I put together a roundup of what I think are the best of the best, by day, with commentary (below). Check out the content and the companies - it\'s worth your time. And if you do nothing else, do these three things: 1. Follow <a href=\"https://twitter.com/tnpuig\">Tomas Puig on Twitter</a>, who\'s workshop with Paul Dery was the single best thing I attended; 2. Buy Rick Webb\'s <a href=\"http://rickwebb.tumblr.com/\"><em>Agency: The Book</em></a><em>, </em>which sold out at SXSW; 3. Check out <a href=\"https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/881308232/only-on-kickstarter-the-leaders-guide-by-eric-ries\">Eric Ries\' crowd-sourced new book</a>, available only on Kickstarter and announced yesterday at SXSW.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Roundup - Day 1</strong></p>\r\n<strong>Panel: <em>How to Remain Relevant in Today’s Digital Age, </em>Charles Barkley and Richard Deistch</strong> The conversation didn’t follow the panel title, but it was entertaining and filled with Barkley’s one-liners and a firm explanation of why he’s not on social media: it’s become a mean-spirited place. My favorite? His take on analytics: <em>Analytics is just stats. They just charge you more when they call it analytics. But it’s just stats.</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Popup: How to Be a Change Agent, Brand Innovators </strong>An oasis in the SXSW storm, Brand Innovators hosted a full day of terrific programming and presentations featuring marketers, tech, and start-ups. If you are a brand marketer and don\'t attend their events, you should. <a href=\"http://brand-innovators.com/events/\">Find their calendar here.</a>\r\n\r\n<strong>Party: NYT Magazine Relaunch Party</strong> Nothing much about the Times or the Magazine, but it did feature a great band, <a href=\"http://www.thesuffers.com/\"><em>The Suffers</em></a><em>, </em>at a classic venue – Mohawk on Red River.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Roundup - Day 2</strong></p>\r\n<strong>Workshop: <em>Adv. Brand Marketing for Early Stage Companies, </em>Paul Dury and Tomas Puig</strong> The single best thing at SXSW. Marketing dollars + activities at early-stage companies need a different approach, and this four-hour workshop featured great content, in a digestible presentation and discussion, led by two experts. From how VC\'s judge a start-up via LTV and CAC to the basics of identifying your target market and USP, and addressing org structure of the modern marketing department, the material here was spot-on. And, contrast of Tomas and Paul\'s backgrounds brought the material to life in a relevant way. <a href=\"https://twitter.com/tnpuig\">Tweet them for slides</a>!\r\n\r\n<strong>Day 2 Party: Rick Webb at the Yieldbot House </strong>Thanks to Yieldbot and Rick Webb for BBQ, Music, and FUN. The party celebrated <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Agency-Starting-Creative-Marketing-Advertising/dp/1137279869\">Rick\'s new book</a>, which is terrific. You can also catch my favorite post of his on Medium <a href=\"https://medium.com/galleys/f-king-timesheets-b3bb9d64beb8\">here</a>.\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Roundup - Day 3</strong></p>\r\n<strong>Day 3 Panel: <em>Future 15s Humans Not Consumers: Unconscious Emotions and Actions</em>, Douglas Van Praet </strong>A fascinating discussion about how we make choices - consciously and unconsciously - driven by emotion. The \"I like it and I don\'t know why\" effect is powerful, and Van Praet makes a good case for marketers to consider \'pattern interruption\' in creative execution. Check out his book <a href=\"http://unconsciousbranding.com/\">here</a>.\r\n\r\n<strong>Day 3 Party: Dropbox </strong>With lots of competing parties, where to go/ Dropbox at <a href=\"http://shop.mellowjohnnys.com/?gclid=CIiAle7Wr8QCFQ8waQodon4ALw\">Mellow Johnny\'s Bike Shop</a>, of course! Great party, and a great 90\'s cover band, Angry Flannel (which founder Drew Houston is a member of). Nirvana, Jane\'s Addiction, represented!\r\n\r\n<strong>Roundup - Day 4</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Panel: <em>Everything Eric Ries Has Learned Since 2011</em>, Eric Ries, Ted Greenwald</strong> Fans of <a href=\"http://theleanstartup.com/\">The Lean Startup</a> author, rejoice! Eric Ries announced a new book, crowd-sourced on Kickstarter, called <a href=\"http://www.fastcompany.com/3043745/most-creative-people/the-lean-startup-author-eric-ries-is-crowdsourcing-his-next-book-via-ki\">The Leader\'s Guide</a>. Don\'t be intimidated - just be entertained - by the number of special \'packages\' you can choose from - it\'s part of the gimmick! For reference, I went with the All-Access Package.\r\n\r\nQuick shout out to my new friends at Tech.co, Chute, Partnered, and General Assembly - great meeting you guys. Rock on, Austin, and see you in 2016!','Hello from Austin and another SXSW!','','publish','open','open','','254','','','2015-03-18 20:07:44','2015-03-18 20:07:44','',0,'http://abbot-water.dev/?p=254',0,'post','',0),
